        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will use the FDM correlator mode with a spectral resolution of 0.976 MHz and a bandwidth of 1875 MHz, which gives us a velocity resolution of ~2.5 km/s in Band 3. We choose Band 3 for its higher sensitivity as compared with other bands, and because its less affected by non-optimal weather conditions, which are difficult to control in the case of a Target of Opportunity observation. In case of need, Band 4 could be used as an alternative. 
We will tune to the frequency range that covers a larger amount of potential absorption features, giving priority to HCO+ and CO, which we expect to produce stronger absorptions. The observation uses 3 hr on target, which would deliver an r.m.s. of ~0.7 mJy (according to the exposure time calculator), meaning that we will have a continuum with a S/N = 5 per spectral bin for a 3.5 mJy source. If the source happens to be dimmer, we would bin the spectrum by a factor of 9, to increase the S/N by 3 and still keep a resolution (22.5 km/s).
The antenna configuration is not critical for this project, aiming at a point source. However ALMA is the only instrument providing both the sensitivity and bandpass stability to carry out the proposed observations.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
