    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to use long GRB afterglows as a beacons to study the chemistry of high-redshift star forming regions, though the observation of molecular absorption features. This is a single trigger target of opportunity proposal where we will obtain spectroscopy of a bright GRB afterglow, with a resolution of 2.5 km/s, aiming to cover as many molecular features as possible, in particular the CO and HCO+ absorption features. The exact spectral features that will be observed will depend on the redshift of the GRB. It will be the first time that GRBs are used in millimetre wavelengths for such purpose and constitute one of the only ways in which to study the molecular chemistry of star forming regions at high-redshift. These data will be combined with optical and near infrared afterglow spectroscopy, of intermediate resolution, obtained with the X-shooter spectrograph at the VLT to produce a complete study of the interstellar medium.</prp:abstract>
